He is also running for school board in Augusta and recently [filed a federal lawsuit against the Augusta Police Department](https://www.centralmaine.com/2026/01/14/flag-wearing-activist-sues-augusta-police-over-detainment-at-no-kings-rally/), which he is accusing of violating his constitutional rights for detaining him as he counterprotested [during a “No Kings” rally](https://www.centralmaine.com/2025/10/18/no-kings-protests-draw-thousands-of-mainers-opposed-to-trump-policies/) in October.

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2026/01/43210786_20251104_maineXwatch_3356.jpg?w=1024)](https://w2pcms.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2025/11/43210786_20251104_maineXwatch_3356.jpg)

Conservative activist and Augusta school board candidate Nicholas “Corn Pop” Blanchard shows a video of his October detention by Augusta police during an Election Night event in November. (Joe Phelan/Staff Photographer)

Blanchard said in an interview Tuesday that he was assaulted after being kicked out of the Thursday evening school board meeting.

[A recording of the meeting](https://youtu.be/CFQB6GW8-qA?si=0aUDTtRKKwwy0-KF) posted to the district’s YouTube account shows someone passing out wine glasses to school board members while Blanchard spoke at the podium during the public comment period. School board members promptly began calling for officers to take Blanchard out of the room.

Kathleen Stanton Whalen, who chairs the school board, said earlier in the meeting that she had been accused of drinking alcohol while participating in a December meeting on Zoom.

